00:22:18,278 --> 00:22:23,790
Scott: Well, one is, you know, based on clicking and one is based on knowledge.

348
00:22:23,850 --> 00:22:25,739
Rym: Well, what's the difference between Jeopardy!

349
00:22:25,759 --> 00:22:27,286
Rym: and, say, football?

350
00:22:28,891 --> 00:22:31,350
Scott: One is based on punching and one is based on knowledge.

351
00:22:31,390 --> 00:22:32,388
Rym: Oh my god, they're all games.

352
00:22:32,790 --> 00:22:32,881
Rym: Yeah.

353
00:22:33,075 --> 00:22:33,388
Rym: Games.

354
00:22:33,910 --> 00:22:34,328
Scott: It's a game show.

355
00:22:34,710 --> 00:22:45,590
Rym: But game shows very specifically have a heavy overlap with either professional sports in the sense that they're made not for the people playing, but for the people watching.

356
00:22:46,110 --> 00:22:51,170
Rym: Game shows are often not actually fun to be on, they're fun to watch other people be on.

357
00:22:51,430 --> 00:22:55,383
Scott: Well, the other thing, well, yeah, they're designed for the spectator first, right?

358
00:22:55,463 --> 00:22:57,410
Scott: And then for the participant second.

359
00:22:57,570 --> 00:22:58,230
Scott: I mean, case in point.

360
00:22:58,410 --> 00:23:01,490
Scott: The participant, most of the excitement for the participant comes from the prize winning.

361
00:23:01,691 --> 00:23:02,173
Scott: Exactly.

362
00:23:02,314 --> 00:23:05,710
Rym: No one is playing most game shows unless there's cash money.

363
00:23:05,950 --> 00:23:15,550
Scott: Right, and the reason for the prize winning is because it's not, like, the difference between this and, say, sports is there isn't, like, a consistent, like, players and teams to root for.

364
00:23:15,930 --> 00:23:17,815
Scott: I mean, someone might keep winning on Jeopardy!

365
00:23:17,875 --> 00:23:23,870
Scott: and gain a following, but usually when you're on a game show, you're on there for a limited time and then you're done.

366
00:23:24,490 --> 00:23:29,310
Scott: So, it's like you're just an individual human being who's just some contestant and that's it.

367
00:23:29,871 --> 00:23:31,575
Scott: So, the prizes are the reward.

368
00:23:31,615 --> 00:23:37,890
Scott: There isn't, like, a grand championship to win or, you know, some trophy or, you know, tournament at the end of every year.

369
00:23:37,910 --> 00:23:39,650
Rym: You're not the league master at Wheel of Fortune.

370
00:23:39,710 --> 00:23:42,970
Scott: Yeah, there's no playoffs at Wheel of Fortune at the end of the year where you can win the wheelie or whatever.

371
00:23:42,970 --> 00:23:44,367
Rym: Well, they do do stuff like that, actually.

372
00:23:45,551 --> 00:23:48,270
Rym: Like, they do have, like, the Masters Series or whatever in a lot of these game shows.

373
00:23:48,270 --> 00:23:52,850
Scott: Yeah, no, but there isn't, like, the Super Bowl every single year at the same time, you know, things like that.

374
00:23:52,990 --> 00:24:21,210
Rym: This is thus why game shows adapted as home additions are an interesting game design challenge because you have a game that, one, is designed primarily for spectation, designed to last a predictable amount of time no matter what, designed to be able to have a lot of stuff happen off-screen to fix issues that you don't show to the spectators, and the players have no capacity to master the game or to find degenerate strategies in the game.

375
00:24:21,311 --> 00:24:23,069
Rym: Usually, they film a whole season of a game show.

376
00:24:23,750 --> 00:24:27,729
Rym: Like, you know, kids would watch Legend of the Hidden Temple and think, "Oh, I could fucking do

377
00:24:27,769 --> 00:24:27,950
Rym: that.".

378
00:24:28,070 --> 00:24:42,510
