00:26:42,450 --> 00:26:44,424
Rym: For like, for Sam, I don't know, like seven, eight bucks?

404
00:26:44,524 --> 00:26:45,350
Rym: I have no idea.

405
00:26:45,452 --> 00:26:45,808
Scott: I don't know.

406
00:26:46,050 --> 00:26:49,481
Rym: But I can tell you that if a bottle of shampoo was on The Price is Right.

407
00:26:49,502 --> 00:26:52,696
Rym: when I was a kid, I would bid $3.95.

408
00:26:52,696 --> 00:26:52,787
Scott: Sure.

409
00:26:53,951 --> 00:27:01,410
Rym: But at the same time, like, a game that Scott and I play way more often than you'd think is Family Feud on the Super Nintendo.

410
00:27:01,510 --> 00:27:06,169
Scott: So Family Feud also has the timeliness problem, at least with some of the categories, right?

411
00:27:06,450 --> 00:27:30,190
Rym: But at the same time, that makes it almost more interesting because if you play Family Feud on the Super Nintendo, you're trying to figure out what a hundred sanitized answers were to a question where you have a very limited amount of memory on a cartridge and limited ability to... For example, if there's a lot of ways to say an answer, they had to hard code a big list of strings that they could match on.

412
00:27:30,250 --> 00:27:53,367
Scott: So that's something that happens in both the Jeopardy for both, like, all video Jeopardies and all video Family Feuds have this same exact issue where you're typing in answers in text and if the computer system that's running the game is not sufficiently advanced, it's not very good at sort.

413
00:27:53,407 --> 00:27:53,467
Scott: of.

414
00:27:53,547 --> 00:27:58,010
Scott: subjectively, you know, examining your answers the way humans could do.

415
00:27:58,070 --> 00:28:03,928
Scott: Like, if you're playing Family Feud for real, they have judges there who run the show who are like, "Yeah, that counts as number three.

416
00:28:04,008 --> 00:28:04,369
Scott: Ding.".

417
00:28:04,650 --> 00:28:05,452
Scott: So here's an example.

418
00:28:05,472 --> 00:28:10,882
Rym: What if a question was like, I don't know, something you give to someone to signify your love for them?

419
00:28:11,223 --> 00:28:14,930
Rym: Should I type in "wedding ring" or just "ring"?

420
00:28:15,692 --> 00:28:21,450
Scott: Yeah, and if that was a modern day computer with some Google-level technology, or even less than that, it can figure it out.

421
00:28:21,811 --> 00:28:22,330
Rym: Yeah, and on a game show...

422
00:28:22,350 --> 00:28:25,449
Scott: But if you're doing this on an NES, good luck.

423
00:28:25,911 --> 00:28:39,590
Rym: Which, again, makes it fun because Scott and I will both know the answer and are trying to furiously type them in by moving a cursor around with a Super Nintendo controller, guessing at what some schmuck developing this thing in 1993.

424
00:28:39,590 --> 00:28:41,068
Scott: What list of strings they typed in.

425
00:28:41,433 --> 00:28:42,130
Rym: In 1993.

426
00:28:42,130 --> 00:28:44,364
Scott: And if you get a spelling error, you're wrong.

427
00:28:44,746 --> 00:28:45,309
Scott: Try again.

428
00:28:46,672 --> 00:28:48,570
Scott: So if you don't know how to spell the word, good luck.

429
00:28:50,551 --> 00:28:55,700
Rym: But at the same time, that Family Feud game is stupid fun as a result, even though it's kind of random.

430
00:28:55,780 --> 00:29:01,009
Rym: It's kind of the same fun as that horse racing game that we always talk about as an example of a bullshit random game.

431
00:29:01,049 --> 00:29:01,770
Rym: that's still really fun.

432
00:29:03,271 --> 00:29:13,030
Scott: Wheel of Fortune actually happens to be an excellent take-home video game, especially the video game, because there is no ambiguity whatsoever.

433
00:29:13,170 --> 00:29:15,654
Scott: You spin a wheel, which a video game is really great at.

434
00:29:16,194 --> 00:29:18,418
Scott: It figures out how much money stuff is.

435
00:29:18,718 --> 00:29:20,741
Scott: You choose the one letter at a time.

436
00:29:20,761 --> 00:29:27,090
Scott: You don't have to type in a whole bunch of stuff until you solve the puzzle, in which case you're literally putting letters in the slots.

437
00:29:27,631 --> 00:29:29,469
Scott: You're either right or you're wrong.

438
00:29:30,931 --> 00:29:33,503
Scott: There's no subjectiveness to it.

439
00:29:33,543 --> 00:29:35,130
Scott: It's very easy for a computer to do.

440
00:29:35,250 --> 00:29:41,870
Scott: So a lot of the take-home Wheel of Fortune's, especially the video game versions, are really good and just as fun as the real thing.

441
00:29:42,393 --> 00:29:44,110
Scott: Only some of the phrases might be outdated.

442
00:29:44,290 --> 00:29:44,453
Rym: Yep.

443
00:29:44,554 --> 00:29:45,509
Rym: Now the board game.

444
00:29:46,290 --> 00:29:49,356
Scott: There's only so many phrases like hard coded into these games.

445
00:29:49,857 --> 00:29:57,470
Scott: So once you know all the phrases like the same thing with the Family Feud, it's all hard coded in like there's a database of, you know, polls in there.

446
00:29:57,871 --> 00:30:00,719
Scott: So if you've memorized all of them, same thing.

447
00:30:00,760 --> 00:30:02,424
Scott: I had junior jeopardy for the NES.

448
00:30:02,444 --> 00:30:04,109
Scott: That really did not have a lot of questions.

449
00:30:05,611 --> 00:30:10,223
Scott: So once you memorize the answers to all of them, you could pretty well dominate.

450
00:30:10,263 --> 00:30:13,150
Scott: The thing was it didn't give you the answers necessarily.

451
00:30:14,172 --> 00:30:16,523
Scott: I guess I'm not sure it did or didn't actually.

452
00:30:16,544 --> 00:30:17,830
Scott: It's been so long since I played it.

453
00:30:17,890 --> 00:30:18,772
Rym: I don't even remember.

454
00:30:18,792 --> 00:30:25,670
Rym: But yeah, so like the, at least the SNES Family Feud has enough stuff in it to where unless one of us like really works at it.

455
00:30:25,770 --> 00:30:27,750
Scott: I have yet to see a repeat on there.

456
00:30:27,950 --> 00:30:30,490
Rym: Or takes the ROM apart and like starts looking for strings.

457
00:30:30,770 --> 00:30:32,149
Scott: Or goes in game facts and prints them out.

458
00:30:32,450 --> 00:30:36,921
Rym: But like the mechanical, physical wheel of fortune I had also worked great.

459
00:30:36,982 --> 00:30:38,225
Rym: Like it worked perfectly.

460
00:30:38,285 --> 00:30:40,210
Rym: It was 100% great to play as a game.

461
00:30:40,830 --> 00:30:49,590
Rym: Except there's only a limited number of those giant pieces of cardboard and a certain brother could just go read them all and know all the answers.

462
00:30:50,150 --> 00:30:51,489
Rym: Like when you play Trivial Pursuit.

463
00:30:52,191 --> 00:30:52,352
Scott: Yeah.

464
00:30:52,372 --> 00:30:54,810
Scott: Good luck memorizing huge decks of Trivial Pursuit cards.

465
00:30:55,251 --> 00:31:00,444
Rym: That's actually at the one time in recent memory I was forced to play a game of Trivial Pursuit.

466
00:31:00,825 --> 00:31:02,730
Rym: It was an addition from like decades ago.

467
00:31:03,591 --> 00:31:08,450
Rym: So I knew more than fucking everybody because I'm the only person who knows politics from the 80s apparently.

468
00:31:09,270 --> 00:31:09,533
Rym: So yeah.

469
00:31:10,906 --> 00:31:11,310
Rym: But anyway.

470
00:31:13,731 --> 00:31:22,050
Rym: So in terms of games like Double Dare, the physical component, like Double Dare is a really shitty game.

471
00:31:22,972 --> 00:31:26,330
Rym: I mean it's a dumb trivia question that only stupid kids couldn't answer.

472
00:31:26,730 --> 00:31:31,206
Rym: You never wanted to take the physical challenge unless you were sure that the other side was really stupid.

473
00:31:31,246 --> 00:31:32,350
Rym: You get the most points that way.

474
00:31:33,450 --> 00:31:40,050
Rym: And a home version of that would actually probably suck because it probably had a bunch of like a little thing to make some slime.

475
00:31:40,890 --> 00:31:43,290
Rym: And like a little Nerf gun kind of thing.

476
00:31:43,630 --> 00:31:48,210
Scott: I think it had the thing where you wear a basket on your head and they throw balls at you and you have to catch them.

477
00:31:48,450 --> 00:31:49,330
Rym: So it's the same physical challenge?

478
00:31:49,711 --> 00:31:49,994
Scott: Yeah.

479
00:31:50,014 --> 00:31:50,964
Scott: That kind of bullshit.

480
00:31:51,207 --> 00:31:51,469
Scott: You know.

481
00:31:51,831 --> 00:32:01,590
Rym: The only reason any kid ever wanted to be on Double Dare was one, because just being on TV was like the most cool thing you could do as a kid in the late 80s in the world culturally.

482
00:32:02,311 --> 00:32:05,089
Rym: Two, cash prizes or like a game gear or whatever.

483
00:32:06,050 --> 00:32:10,562
Rym: And three, because if you got to the optical course, I didn't even want to win.

484
00:32:10,602 --> 00:32:13,390
Rym: I just wanted to be on the show so I could play in a giant optical course.

485
00:32:13,610 --> 00:32:14,936
Scott: Well they also had family Double Dare.

486
00:32:15,137 --> 00:32:17,990
Scott: It's like yeah, my parents answer the trivia questions.

487
00:32:18,270 --> 00:32:20,590
Rym: And then I'll run through the giant gumball machine.

488
00:32:20,590 --> 00:32:21,896
Scott: And they'll also get all messy.

489
00:32:21,916 --> 00:32:25,090
Scott: And then the third they had Super Sloppy Double Dare.

490
00:32:25,550 --> 00:32:34,250
Scott: Which I don't remember very well obviously, but I don't remember Super Sloppy Double Dare being any super or sloppier than any other Double Dare.

491
00:32:35,611 --> 00:32:36,548
Scott: I think they just called it that.

492
00:32:37,070 --> 00:32:45,008
Rym: So you know, if I was going to make a Double Dare home edition, the way I would do it, actually when I think about it, the problem is the trivia part is 90% of the game.

493
00:32:46,931 --> 00:32:51,425
Rym: So you'd have to change the score structure around some way, but you could do the physical challenges like this.

494
00:32:51,786 --> 00:32:52,970
Rym: It's horse in the real world.

495
00:32:53,490 --> 00:32:54,915
Rym: So you know the game of horse, basketball game?

496
00:32:55,377 --> 00:32:59,070
Rym: So I do something, you have to do the same thing I did.

497
00:32:59,190 --> 00:33:03,670
Rym: So the physical challenge is I'm going to do something, whatever that is.

498
00:33:03,730 --> 00:33:04,680
Scott: So a completely different game.

499
00:33:04,700 --> 00:33:05,610
Scott: that's nothing to do with Double Dare.

500
00:33:05,830 --> 00:33:07,195
Rym: Well it's just a physical challenge.

501
00:33:07,215 --> 00:33:11,129
Rym: because how do you generate physical challenges with a board game box?

502
00:33:12,231 --> 00:33:17,569
Scott: They include the list of physical challenges and the necessary equipment on a piece of paper and charge you money for it.

503
00:33:18,170 --> 00:33:20,269
Rym: So how much equipment can you possibly fit in that box?

504
00:33:20,570 --> 00:33:21,869
Scott: Go look it up and you'll see what's in there.

505
00:33:22,390 --> 00:33:24,010
Rym: I think it's just really lame probably.

506
00:33:24,310 --> 00:33:25,497
Scott: It's pretty lame, yeah.

507
00:33:26,362 --> 00:33:27,367
Scott: Just look for Double Dare.

508
00:33:27,428 --> 00:33:27,830
Scott: take home.

509
00:33:29,232 --> 00:33:31,990
Rym: I thought Double Dare box and it was like Double Dare box wine?

510
00:33:32,818 --> 00:33:32,986
Scott: No.

511
00:33:33,871 --> 00:33:35,588
Rym: Double Dare box shot for the NES.

512
00:33:36,390 --> 00:33:36,570
Scott: What?

513
00:33:37,575 --> 00:33:37,805
Scott: Wow.

514
00:33:38,212 --> 00:33:40,343
Scott: Oh no that's the box of the NES.

515
00:33:40,403 --> 00:33:41,590
Scott: take home video game.

516
00:33:41,770 --> 00:33:42,454
Scott: Do you dare?

517
00:33:42,614 --> 00:33:43,559
Rym: Can you handle the pressure?

518
00:33:43,600 --> 00:33:44,364
Rym: Do you know the answer?

519
00:33:44,384 --> 00:33:45,510
Scott: Do you dare the other team?

520
00:33:45,970 --> 00:33:46,752
Scott: I played that once.

521
00:33:48,175 --> 00:33:54,610
Scott: Basically it's just trivia questions which are multiple choice and the physical challenges and obviously of course the little mini games that kind of sucked.

522
00:33:55,030 --> 00:33:57,890
Rym: The mini games look a lot like the mini games in the Three Stooges game.

523
00:33:58,150 --> 00:33:59,477
Scott: See that Jeopardy Junior edition?

524
00:33:59,497 --> 00:34:00,462
Scott: I had that.

525
00:34:00,482 --> 00:34:01,950
Scott: I had that cartridge.

526
00:34:02,811 --> 00:34:03,112
Scott: Alright.

527
00:34:04,036 --> 00:34:06,989
Scott: Are there any other take home games?

528
00:34:07,430 --> 00:34:15,969
Scott: So actually one thing I do want to talk about is things that are video games or take home games that are like game shows but never were actually game shows.

529
00:34:16,650 --> 00:34:23,127
Scott: The most prominent of which is You Don't Know Jack which is basically a game show but it was never on TV.

530
00:34:23,147 --> 00:34:24,190
Scott: It was just a video game.

531
00:34:24,810 --> 00:34:28,650
Scott: And You Don't Know Jack can actually be kind of fun in the right scenario.

532
00:34:29,571 --> 00:34:49,449
Scott: If people don't know how You Don't Know Jack works it's basically you sit around a computer or TV screen or whatever and it sort of does these real time challenges where you're sort of answering questions or doing other sort of games and there's a lot of push the button first kind of stuff and things like that.

533
00:34:50,070 --> 00:34:51,657
Scott: And it's actually when it came out.

534
00:34:51,697 --> 00:34:54,469
Scott: it was incredibly clever and nowadays it seems a little bit silly.

535
00:34:54,996 --> 00:34:55,288
Rym: No.

536
00:34:55,710 --> 00:34:58,294
Scott: But it's had some resurgences over the years.

537
00:34:58,714 --> 00:35:11,130
Scott: So if you've got some kind of family thing going on and your family can't exactly play Counter Strike this is not a bad choice compared to other games that might be available.

538
00:35:11,150 --> 00:35:12,251
Rym: This is sort of the rub.

539
00:35:12,732 --> 00:35:19,059
Rym: Take home games like the home edition of any game show is almost guaranteed to fail unless you're really clever.

540
00:35:19,119 --> 00:35:28,350
Rym: or the game is trivially adaptable like Wheel of Fortune is because if you deviate from what happens on TV at all the family who sits down to play is going to be like what this is bullshit.

541
00:35:28,530 --> 00:35:31,730
Scott: Right so that's part of the advantage of it is like the family already knows how to play.

542
00:35:31,790 --> 00:35:36,495
Rym: So you can't change anything but at the same time if you don't change anything.

543
00:35:36,796 --> 00:35:40,460
Rym: the game's not designed to be played by people who play it more than once.

544
00:35:40,540 --> 00:35:50,010
Rym: nor is it designed to be played in a setting that doesn't have judges and officiants and extra content and all these outside forces and it's aimed only for spectators.

545
00:35:50,250 --> 00:35:50,616
Scott: It's a good thing.

546
00:35:50,636 --> 00:35:51,529
Scott: most of them are just trivia.

547
00:35:52,310 --> 00:35:52,390
Scott: Yes.

548
00:35:53,590 --> 00:35:57,063
Scott: Because anyone can just knows how to answer trivia questions like win lose or draw.

549
00:35:57,083 --> 00:35:58,930
Scott: at Pictionary you're basically the same goddamn thing.

550
00:35:59,471 --> 00:36:16,950
Rym: Now the real thing to take away from the design of like the take home editions of these kinds of games that really in this age of Twitch these kinds of games are actually great for like Twitch kind of live streaming play because very few people play most people are just watching.

551
00:36:17,590 --> 00:36:19,230
Scott: But they're designed for spectators.

552
00:36:20,790 --> 00:36:26,830
Rym: So as a result these games are probably better for that sort of thing than like Counter Strike for the average person.

553
00:36:28,865 --> 00:36:28,970
Scott: Yeah.

554
00:36:29,190 --> 00:36:33,190
Scott: So when you're home with your family this holiday time play torchbearer.

555
00:36:33,598 --> 00:36:33,870
Rym: Yeah.

556
00:36:34,091 --> 00:36:37,430
Scott: If you want to get a game going on and you're have you're reaching to the bottom of the barrel.

557
00:36:37,754 --> 00:36:38,948
Scott: They don't even want to play Hanabi.

558
00:36:39,578 --> 00:36:39,808
Scott: Yeah.

559
00:36:40,215 --> 00:36:41,009
Scott: They're so lame.

560
00:36:41,812 --> 00:36:43,610
Scott: The game show game might work.

561
00:36:43,750 --> 00:36:44,849
Scott: It might open the door.

562
00:36:45,330 --> 00:36:45,968
Scott: Don't knock.

563
00:36:47,032 --> 00:36:48,530
Scott: I had myself in the teeth of the microphone.

564
00:36:48,880 --> 00:36:49,048
Scott: Wow.

565
00:36:49,311 --> 00:36:51,470
Rym: And for once it wasn't me like bumping into the boom.

566
00:36:51,570 --> 00:36:52,107
Rym: That was all you.

567
00:36:52,415 --> 00:36:52,670
Rym: Yeah.

568
00:36:53,112 --> 00:36:53,906
Scott: So consider them.

569
00:36:54,754 --> 00:36:55,910
Rym: Well especially the thing is don't.

570
00:36:56,499 --> 00:36:57,148
Rym: I would say this.

571
00:36:57,730 --> 00:37:04,950
Rym: Skip the ones that are just trivia questions because those always fail if anyone knows shit about anything.

572
00:37:05,770 --> 00:37:06,690
Rym: And then someone gets mad.

573
00:37:06,790 --> 00:37:10,499
Rym: You're better off going with the ones that are straight party games or where it's like.

574
00:37:10,539 --> 00:37:14,790
Rym: the answers are like Family Feud is probably the best possible game to play.

575
00:37:16,236 --> 00:37:17,229
Rym: Of those kinds of games.

576
00:37:17,710 --> 00:37:19,090
Rym: Maybe Wheel of Fortune is a good second.

577
00:37:19,190 --> 00:37:22,369
Rym: Jeopardy probably not actually going to work with the average family.

578
00:37:23,190 --> 00:37:23,889
Scott: The junior edition.

579
00:37:24,350 --> 00:37:24,530
Rym: Yeah.

